## 1. Locks (machine-readable)

Agents use this block to decide whether a given stage can run. A stage can only start when its predecessors are all `locked`.

```yaml
locks:
  00-new-review:                pending   # pending | locked
  01-research-questions:        pending
  02-search-string:             pending
  03-parse-references-metadata: pending
  04-title-screening:           pending
  05-abstract-screening:        pending
  06-full-text-screening:       pending
  07-taxonomy-development:      pending   # has intermediate `iterating` state during inductive loop
  08-analysis:                  pending
  09-report:                    pending
```

## 2. Theme

`<1–2 paragraphs describing the domain, its practical relevance, and the boundary of what this review covers and does not cover. Filled by /01-research-questions.>`

**Screening doctrine.** When in doubt at title or abstract stages, prefer Include. A false positive costs one extra read at the next stage; a false negative loses a relevant paper forever. Stage 06 has no recall-preserving rule — ambiguity is resolved by reading deeper. The two-pass screening architecture (deterministic regex classifier + single LLM reviewer) is specified in `agents/_screening-protocol.md §1–§3`. The runtime config — categories, patterns, overrides — lives in `protocols/classifier-config.json` (or a stage-specific path declared in §6 below); the file is generated from scratch via Q&A on first run of `/04-title-screening` and reused or refined at later stages.

